@node "installation" "SnowPlants.guide/installation"
First unpack the archive with:
    lha -xa x GB_SnowPlants.lha ram:
(Probably you've done that already.)

Then just click on the install icon and follow the instructions.


If you really want to do it all manually read on:
Just copy the files:
    SnowPlants
    SnowPlants.ifc
    SnowPlants.prefs
    SnowPlants.txt
to the directory containing your Garshneblanker modules.
The file
    SnowPlants.guide
contains this documentation. Copy it where you want
(if you want :)
If you are interested in the source code then make a
subdirectory called SnowPlants in your development tree:
    dev/garshneblanker/blankers/SnowPlants
and copy there the contents of the
    dev
directory of this archive



That's all.
To see it working just use "Exchange" to open Garshneblanker's
front-end, click on "settings" then on "save" and finally select
"SnowPlants" from the menu via a left button double click.
I think the gadgets are quite self-explanatory.
If not, see the @{"parameters" link parameters } section of this guide.
@endnode

@node "parameters" "SnowPlants.guide/Parameters"
À Cycle gadget "Draw falling points, too"
        yes -> Every point is drawn during its way down.
               This results in a much slower picture construction.
        no  -> Each point is only drawn when it finally sticks
               somewhere. Very fast.
        default: no

À Cycle gadget "Colours"
        white       -> all points are white
        random      -> all points have the same colour, thus the
                       picture will be monochrom. The colour is
                       randomly selected on each module startup
        cycle       -> all points have the same colour, thus the
                       picture will be monochrom again.
                       The colour is constantly cycling.
                       You can adjust the cycling speed with the
                       slider "Colourcycling delay".
        copper      -> All pixels have colour one.
                       But this colour is changed by the standard
                       Garshneblanker copperlist depending on the
                       y-coordinate of the pixel's position.
                       So pixels at the bottom are red, higher up
                       they are orange, yellow, green, blue - like
                       a rainbow.
        multicolour -> All other selections use a screen depth of
                       one, regardless your settings in the display
                       requester. This mode is the only multi-
                       coloured display. After a certain number
                       of points the point colour for the next
                       point is changed. You can select the number
                       of pixels drawn in one colour with the slider
                       "Colourcycling delay"
        default: multicolour

À Slider "Colourcycling delay"
        1..5000     -> This value normally sets the speed or better:
                       the "slowness" of the colour cycling mode.
                       In multicolour mode it is the number of points
                       drawn in the same colour
        default: 111

À Slider "Points"
        100..500000 -> Number of points which build one picture.
                       If enough points have fallen down, the module
                       stops, waits some time and then starts a new
                       picture.
                       (You should adapt this value, if you switch to
                       another screen resolution, 'cause a 320*256
                       screen has less pixels than a 1280*1024 screen.)
        default: 30000

À Slider "Max Height"
        10..1280    -> Maximum height of one picture in pixels
                       (you can safely set this to big values, if you
                       want the picture ended only by a maximum number
                       of points.)
        default: 1280

À Cycle gadget <noname>
        "Random aperture, max. is"
                    -> The aperture is randomly selected for each new
                       point. The maximum aperture is specified by the
                       slider gadget to the right.
                       (The higher the aperture the slower may the
                       points fall. Aperture 0 means that all pixels
                       fall vertically, 180 allows them to "fall" almost
                       horizontally.)
        "Strict aperture is"
                    -> The aperture is fixed to the value specified
                       in the slider to the right

        default: "Random aperture, max. is"

À Slider <noname>
        0..180 -> Sets an aperture (see above)
        default: 180

À Slider "Pixel delay"
        1..300 -> This value normally sets the speed or better:
                  the "slowness" of the pixel movement.
                  (Thus "1" is fastest.)
        default: 1

À Slider "Picture delay"
        1..300 -> This value specifies how much time to wait
                  between ending one picture and beginning the
                  next. (Value means seconds)
        default: 10

À Display
        In the display requester you can set your favourite
        display mode. Note that the finer the resolution the more
        points you need for a nice picture, thus the construction
        time rises.
        If you choose more than one colour this has only an effect
        on the multicolour mode (see "cycle gadget >colours<").
@endnode


